When we did test 1, we went outside, waited for the sensor to get data, and then went inside until the next measuring time. For test 2,  we left the sensor running all day and checked the data when the measuring time came. 
We assume that going in and out caused a bigger error, and we find that the results suport that claim. While we recieved better data during the second test, we still didn't recieve great data. This is because the sensor is old
and the sensor gets worse over time
 
